03:56.677 --> 03:59.750
(dramatic music)

03:59.750 --> 04:00.992
Wow.

04:00.992 --> 04:03.685
(jaunty music)

04:06.136 --> 04:07.580
You're kidding me.

04:07.580 --> 04:08.449
It's locked.

04:08.449 --> 04:09.739
That's not very welcoming.

04:11.997 --> 04:14.865
(dramatic music)

04:16.253 --> 04:18.946
(jaunty music)

04:24.667 --> 04:26.047
Why would you have a big mansion

04:26.047 --> 04:29.637
that guests can't arrive
through the front fucking door?

04:30.968 --> 04:33.471
Jesus, who wants to enter
through the back door?

04:34.774 --> 04:37.885
- Mr. Ramsay's here, I need
you to do Room One, right away.

04:41.562 --> 04:44.054
- [Gordon] Well, at
least this door's open.

04:44.054 --> 04:45.316
Finally.
- Hello there.

04:45.316 --> 04:47.057
- How are you?
- How are you, Mr. Ramsay?

04:47.057 --> 04:48.757
- Gordon, please, bloody
hell, what a nightmare.

04:48.757 --> 04:49.852
- I'm Robert Dean.

04:49.852 --> 04:50.720
- Robert Dean.

04:52.052 --> 04:52.921
- Were you over there?

04:52.921 --> 04:54.263
- [Gordon] I was at the front door, yes.

04:54.263 --> 04:56.619
- Okay, this is actually our
entrance and in the winter,

04:56.619 --> 04:59.591
because of snow, we
have to keep that locked

04:59.591 --> 05:02.886
because otherwise the snow load
comes off and kills people.

05:02.886 --> 05:04.585
- Kills people?
- Yeah, it can.

05:04.585 --> 05:05.617
- Have you killed anyone so far?

05:05.617 --> 05:08.808
- No. (laughs)

05:08.808 --> 05:10.013
- Where's all this stuff from?

05:10.013 --> 05:13.141
(suspenseful music)

05:14.335 --> 05:17.129
An aftermath of a antiques fair.

05:17.129 --> 05:18.488
This looks like it could
be a beautiful room,

05:18.488 --> 05:20.289
but you can't tell because it's stuffed

05:20.289 --> 05:21.404
with so much clutter.

05:21.404 --> 05:22.384
That's the reception desk?

05:22.384 --> 05:23.253
- [Robert] No.

05:23.253 --> 05:24.428
- [Gordon] My God, so what is that?

05:24.428 --> 05:25.940
- That is our bar, right now.

05:25.940 --> 05:27.796
- [Gordon] You are kidding
me, this is the bar?

05:27.796 --> 05:29.006
- Yes.
- With what, that?

05:29.006 --> 05:30.445
- [Robert] Martinis.
- Martinis.

05:30.445 --> 05:31.967
Well, God bless him.

05:31.967 --> 05:33.458
Made of pigs, pig martini?

05:33.458 --> 05:35.637
- Well, we have three
rescue pot bellied pigs.

05:35.637 --> 05:36.597
- You have three pigs here?

05:36.597 --> 05:38.025
- Right.

05:38.025 --> 05:39.537
- What is that for?

05:39.537 --> 05:40.872
Were you born with this in your mouth?

05:40.872 --> 05:41.740
- Yeah, don't I wish.

05:41.740 --> 05:42.609
- [Gordon] Honestly?

05:42.609 --> 05:44.229
- Actually, no, that was a gift from-

05:44.229 --> 05:45.098
- A giant?

05:45.098 --> 05:46.523
- So, yeah. (laughs)

05:46.523 --> 05:47.806
- [Gordon] Robert
obviously loves to show off

05:47.806 --> 05:49.855
all his expensive antiques, but as a guest

05:49.855 --> 05:51.549
I don't feel comfortable.

05:51.549 --> 05:53.739
I feel like I'm in a museum.

05:53.739 --> 05:56.168
- [Robert] This is the
main formal dining room.

05:56.168 --> 05:58.681
- This big chair here is for one?

05:58.681 --> 06:02.424
- Just kind of, we're known
as a romantic destination and-

06:02.424 --> 06:03.293
- Just out of interest, how do?

06:03.293 --> 06:04.718
- Well, we would move the table.

06:04.718 --> 06:05.587
- Move it in for me, please.

06:05.587 --> 06:06.652
- [Robert] Yes.

06:06.652 --> 06:09.346
(lilting music)

06:09.346 --> 06:12.497
- Wow, so you got a sofa on the table.

06:12.497 --> 06:14.071
- We thought it was kind of nice to have,

06:14.071 --> 06:15.722
like, a cosy banquette.

06:16.906 --> 06:17.836
- Ugh.

06:17.836 --> 06:20.119
- Well, three US
presidents have dined here.

06:20.119 --> 06:21.235
- [Gordon] Oh really, which ones?

06:21.235 --> 06:23.070
- Teddy Roosevelt, Calvin Coolidge.

06:23.070 --> 06:25.239
- Teddy Roosevelt dined in here, wow.

06:25.239 --> 06:26.834
- I wanted to try to give him

06:26.834 --> 06:29.670
a little bit of sense of
the history of Juniper Hill.

06:29.670 --> 06:31.798
- Wow, okay, so that's the dining room.

06:31.798 --> 06:33.654
- [Robert] Well, we have two dining rooms.

06:33.654 --> 06:36.281
- God, you must be busy
with two dining rooms.

06:36.281 --> 06:38.356
- [Robert] Well, I wish we were busy.

06:38.356 --> 06:39.274
- [Gordon] Bloody hell.

06:39.274 --> 06:42.176
- We have spurts of being incredibly busy.

06:43.184 --> 06:45.561
Where we lack is all the other times.

06:45.561 --> 06:46.500
- Really?
- Yeah.

06:47.584 --> 06:49.732
- This place looks like
a millionaire's mansion,

06:49.732 --> 06:51.119
not a struggling business.

06:51.119 --> 06:53.715
I've got to scratch beneath the surface.

06:53.715 --> 06:56.416
This place, per week, is turning how much?

06:56.416 --> 07:00.076
- We're lucky if we're doing,
you know, 15,000 a month.

07:00.076 --> 07:02.161
- What does it cost to
keep the place open?

07:02.161 --> 07:03.562
- 30.

07:03.562 --> 07:04.865
- Really?
- Yep.

07:06.290 --> 07:10.743
- So you're losing $200,000 a year?

07:10.743 --> 07:12.171
- It's been a nightmare.

07:12.171 --> 07:14.100
We maintained our room rates, thinking

07:14.100 --> 07:16.868
that the economy wouldn't
be this long a haul.

07:16.868 --> 07:19.543
- But we've all experienced
those kind of difficulties,

07:19.543 --> 07:21.253
myself included, but you navigate

07:21.253 --> 07:22.254
your way of that recession.

07:22.254 --> 07:25.143
- Unfortunately, my partner lost his job.

07:25.143 --> 07:27.989
We expected him to have his
job for a little longer.

07:27.989 --> 07:31.451
- He must've gained a substantial
pay-off or retirement?

07:31.451 --> 07:32.848
- It's all been put into this.

07:32.848 --> 07:34.089
- How much?

07:34.089 --> 07:34.975
- Over a million dollars.

07:34.975 --> 07:37.165
- A million dollars, into this already?

07:37.165 --> 07:38.249
- Yes.

07:38.249 --> 07:39.834
- And does he have an
active role in the business?

07:39.834 --> 07:41.649
- He tries to maintain the accounting

07:41.649 --> 07:44.673
and he helps just about with everything.

07:44.673 --> 07:46.070
We're in trouble.

07:46.070 --> 07:46.938
- Trouble?

07:46.938 --> 07:48.259
You'd never guess by
the look of this place.

07:48.259 --> 07:50.918
It's more like Buckingham
Palace than the Skid Row.

07:50.918 --> 07:51.787
Do you know what, Robert, honestly,

07:51.787 --> 07:53.369
I'd like to go straight to my room

07:53.369 --> 07:54.686
if you wouldn't mind, please.

07:54.686 --> 07:55.554
- Okay, all right.

07:55.554 --> 07:56.737
- [Gordon] Wow, this place goes on.

07:56.737 --> 07:57.904
- [Robert] It does, it's the largest

07:57.904 --> 07:59.948
colonial revival mansion in New England.

07:59.948 --> 08:00.845
- [Gordon] And more paintings.

08:00.845 --> 08:03.076
- [Robert] And you're in
the Maxwell Evarts suite,

08:03.076 --> 08:04.630
which is the original.

08:04.630 --> 08:06.406
- Okay, wow, beautiful room.

08:10.691 --> 08:12.426
I mean, this is a,

08:12.426 --> 08:15.783
this is a beautiful room,
but what is that smell?

08:15.783 --> 08:17.589
I mean, seriously.

08:17.589 --> 08:18.457
- It does smell.

08:18.457 --> 08:20.396
- Yeah, but it smells like shit.

08:20.396 --> 08:22.971
I mean, that is horrific.

08:22.971 --> 08:25.227
Oh my God, it smells like sewage.

08:28.216 --> 08:30.249
Coming up, Robert's staff turn on him.

08:30.249 --> 08:32.022
- I'm supposed to tell
you the truth, right?

08:32.022 --> 08:33.544
- The truth is all I want to know.

08:33.544 --> 08:34.879
- I'm telling you exactly how I feel

08:34.879 --> 08:37.288
and how the people that I work with feel.

08:37.288 --> 08:38.873
The entire staff is ready to walk out.

08:38.873 --> 08:41.207
- You can talk to him,
he's your fucking chef.

08:41.207 --> 08:44.044
- I'm beyond angry, I'm beyond pissed off.

08:44.044 --> 08:46.130
- And I have to step in.

08:46.130 --> 08:47.882
How dare you?

08:47.882 --> 08:49.609
You still haven't got it.

08:49.609 --> 08:51.229
Get your head out of your ass

08:51.229 --> 08:53.106
and start getting a little fucking real.

08:53.106 --> 08:54.628
- Excuse me.

08:54.628 --> 08:56.710
- Go on then, you pompous fuck.

08:56.710 --> 08:59.578
(dramatic music)

09:02.290 --> 09:03.957
I'm at Vermont's Juniper Hill Inn,

09:03.957 --> 09:06.953
and I've just met its
owner, Robert Dean II,

09:06.953 --> 09:10.175
who's filled his hotel with
expensive art and antiques.

09:10.175 --> 09:11.666
Were you born with this in your mouth?

09:11.666 --> 09:14.846
But he can't fill his rooms,
and his business is struggling.

09:14.846 --> 09:17.995
You're losing $200,000 a year?

09:17.995 --> 09:18.986
- It's been a nightmare.

09:18.986 --> 09:20.299
- And no wonder, because

09:20.299 --> 09:22.041
although the room he's
put me in looks nice.

09:22.041 --> 09:22.909
Beautiful room.

09:22.909 --> 09:24.616
It has one major drawback.

09:24.616 --> 09:25.951
What is that smell?

09:25.951 --> 09:28.485
It smells like raw sewage.

09:28.485 --> 09:29.746
- We had a plumbing issue and-

09:29.746 --> 09:32.812
- It's like someone's
shat under the bed, and-

09:32.812 --> 09:33.680
How much?

09:33.680 --> 09:37.177
- This room goes for $350 a night.

09:37.177 --> 09:40.267
- $350 a night for a
room that smells of shit.

09:40.267 --> 09:41.498
You are kidding me?

09:41.498 --> 09:42.801
- [Robert] We haven't rented it, though.

09:42.801 --> 09:43.948
- Bloody hell.

09:43.948 --> 09:46.742
- It's been out of use for four months.

09:46.742 --> 09:48.578
- Four months?

09:48.578 --> 09:49.446
Oh, come on.

09:49.446 --> 09:50.872
- It has been.
- This is crazy.

09:50.872 --> 09:51.740
- It is crazy.

09:51.740 --> 09:52.609
- It doesn't make sense.

09:52.609 --> 09:53.822
I've got to get out of
here, it stinks of shit.

09:53.822 --> 09:54.691
Is there another room, please?

09:54.691 --> 09:55.626
- Yes, I have Room Two.

09:55.626 --> 09:56.495
- Bloody hell.

09:56.495 --> 09:59.800
- I didn't realise.
- $350, to be caked in shit.

10:01.591 --> 10:04.656
Wow, it's gorgeous, and this
one doesn't smell like crap.

10:04.656 --> 10:06.199
I'm gonna quickly unpack,

10:06.199 --> 10:09.672
and then I would like to
have a quick bite of lunch.

10:09.672 --> 10:11.593
- [Robert] Okay, I'll notify the chef.

10:11.593 --> 10:12.696
- What time's the
restaurant close for lunch?

10:12.696 --> 10:13.564
I know it's two o'clock.

10:13.564 --> 10:15.563
- Well, we actually don't
serve lunch normally,

10:15.563 --> 10:17.867
but we're happy to prepare you something.

10:17.867 --> 10:19.108
- Is that a joke?

10:19.108 --> 10:19.977
- We serve breakfast and dinner.

10:19.977 --> 10:22.132
- No, no, stop, stop, stop, stop, stop.

10:22.132 --> 10:24.144
You don't actually serve lunch?

10:24.144 --> 10:25.013
- No.

10:25.013 --> 10:25.882
- The restaurant's closed for lunch?

10:25.882 --> 10:27.450
- Yes, if someone requests lunch

10:27.450 --> 10:29.139
we'll make lunch for them, but-

10:29.139 --> 10:31.235
- Could you prepare lunch for me?

10:31.235 --> 10:33.310
- Ah, yes, I can, I'll tell the chef.

10:33.310 --> 10:34.582
- Please.
- Okay.

10:34.582 --> 10:36.813
- [Gordon] Thank you.
- Yes, sir.

10:36.813 --> 10:38.774
- Not open for lunch.

10:38.774 --> 10:40.703
- [Robert] Gordon is gonna want lunch.

10:40.703 --> 10:41.571
- Huh?

10:41.571 --> 10:42.440
- Gordon wants lunch.

10:43.487 --> 10:46.563
- What am I supposed to
do with that information?

10:46.563 --> 10:49.337
(birds chirping)

10:49.337 --> 10:52.068
- (sighs) That is a
welcome breath of fresh air

10:52.068 --> 10:54.727
on the back of that disgusting
smell of crap in that room,

10:54.727 --> 10:55.596
I can't believe it.

10:55.596 --> 10:57.209
And the rooms are gorgeous, and yet

10:57.209 --> 11:00.931
how could you have a room that
has been smelling for months

11:00.931 --> 11:03.658
that bad and then he sticks me in it?

11:03.658 --> 11:04.527
What a muppet.

11:07.907 --> 11:10.566
Despite the hideous smell
in that first guest room,

11:11.577 --> 11:13.371
I've still worked up quite an appetite.

11:13.371 --> 11:14.445
Hello.

11:14.445 --> 11:15.998
- Hi, how are you?

11:15.998 --> 11:16.867
Barbara.
- Barbara.

11:16.867 --> 11:17.792
How glamorous are you?

11:17.792 --> 11:19.752
- How nice to see you.
- [Gordon] Likewise.

11:19.752 --> 11:21.389
- I have a mad crush on Gordon.

11:21.389 --> 11:23.662
As he knows, I'm a cougar.

11:23.662 --> 11:24.630
- How old are you now?

11:24.630 --> 11:26.738
- I'm old.
